1 Exploratory Data Analysis

Analysis of Titanic Passenger Surival

Using Titanic dataset

Using dplyr R package

  • for data wrangling and feature engineering

  • dplyr makes you much more productive and far more intuitive

  • Look at the help resources ?dplyr

  • dplyr: a grammar of data manipulation collection of functions that makes working with data

1.1 Why do feature engineering?

In most Data Science scenarios, Feature Engineering is paramount

  • Feature engineering often trumps algorithms, more data, parameter tuning, etc.

Data Scientist spend 60-80% of their time on being data janitors

  • getting data, understanding data, cleaning data, feature engineering commonly referred to as data wrangling

Faster data wrangling == more business value!

  • if you can do data wrangling faster - you can compete much much more effective

To win Kaggle - feature engineering is most important

In business textual data is more than numeric data categorical data is more common categorical data - think of dropdown with US states discrete variables It is important to learn to work with string data

1.2 Types of Joins

1.2.1 left_join

  • all rows of primary table and matching rows of right

1.2.2 right_join

  • all rows of secondary table and only matching rows of primary table

1.2.3 inner_join

  • only match rows from primary and secondary tables

1.2.4 full_join

  • all rows from both tables and matching rows

1.2.5 semi_join

  • rows & columns only from primary table that have matching in secondary table
  • no data from second table is shown

1.2.6 anti-join

  • rows & columns from primary table that don’t have matches in second table

1.3 What is Imputation?

  • It is data cleansing step of data analysis in which we deduce the missing (NA) values
  • or values that are incorrect based on the domain knowledge of the case study.

For example, in the Titanic Passenger Survival dataset, there are many observations with missing ‘Age’ values and there are observations where ‘Fare’ is zero. After analysing we use generalization to assign the mean/median value based on the similarity of the missing data point wrt to other data points.

1.4 Steps for Imputing missing values

We mostly followed the below step in our imputation process:

1.4.1 Stats subset

To understand the distribution of the feature we want to impute we create a subset of statistical measures like min, max, mean, median, IQR, variance(var), standard deviation (sd), sum/count etc.

1.4.2 Analyse stats

In this step, we view the statistics subset to analyse what would be the best value to assign, mean or median, for imputation. If the feature distribution is not skewed, that is there is not much variation between the min/max, we can use the mean for the missing values. However, if the distribution has extreme values we can use median. Note. Mean is a computed value affected by min and max hence in case of skewed data median is a better generalisation than mean for missing values.

1.4.3 Indicator variable

We create an indicator variable with values Y (for yes) and N (for no) to serve as a flag to indicate if the observation has imputed values for a specific variable. For example, variable ‘AgeMissing’ indicates whether age is imputed or not. This helps in reverse engineer if at all we need to the original value in later stages of analysis or while building the prediction model.

1.4.4 Lookup table

After we have decided on what statistics/values to use for imputation we create a lookup table with the new values and the common feature by which we will join the lookup table with the original table. If we’re dealing with GroupWise imputation you might have to consider adding the group column and the common columns. For example, ‘Fare’ depends on the passenger class - price of first class is bound to be more than other classes and hence mean of the first class will be different than the mean of other classes.

1.4.5 Left Join the lookup subset

Join the original dataset with the lookup subset using the appropriate join columns. This step adds the new columns to the original dataset - you can crosscheck using the names command.

1.4.6 Impute the values

Use the mutate dplyr command to assign the new values to the feature being imputed based on the appropriate conditions. For example, use the indicator flag and then apply the condition.

1.4.7 Crosscheck

It is important to cross check that all the imputations have been applied correctly. Use summary command on the imputed feature to see if there are any NAs or wrong values. If there are errors, then revisit the code and check the conditions in mutate command.

1.4.8 Remove the additional columns

After assigning the appropriate statistic/value to the missing values using lookup table column values, their purpose is served and they should be removed from the original dataset. Use select(-column) or set the column to NULL to remove the columns.

5.2.1 Create new feature title from name

Let’s create a new feature title from the name variable by extracting the pattern which has characters followed by .

Regex - starts with char and followed by . pattern - one or more letter [a-zA-Z] and immediately a dot + –> one of more, * –> zero or more

First let’s try an example

my_name = " Shobha, Ms. Mourya Shivnarayan"

my_title = str_extract(my_name, pattern = "[a-zA-Z]+\\.")
my_title
## [1] "Ms."
my_name = " Shobha, Miss. Mourya Shivnarayan"
my_title = str_extract(my_name, pattern = "[a-zA-Z]+\\.")
my_title
## [1] "Miss."
my_name = " Shobha, . Mourya Shivnarayan"
my_title = str_extract(my_name, pattern = "[a-zA-Z]+\\.")
my_title
## [1] NA
train = train %>%
  mutate(title = str_extract(name,"[a-zA-Z]+\\."))

table(train$title)
## 
##     Capt.      Col. Countess.      Don.       Dr. Jonkheer.     Lady. 
##         1         2         1         1         7         1         1 
##    Major.   Master.     Miss.     Mlle.      Mme.       Mr.      Mrs. 
##         2        40       182         2         1       517       125 
##       Ms.      Rev.      Sir. 
##         1         6         1
length(unique(train$Title))
## [1] 0

There are a lot of titles with only 1 occurence, Now this is not good for ML algo for example, if there is one Jonkheer who perished then the ML algo will always zero-down on that and predict that a passenger with title Jonkheer will perish this is a clear case of overfitting maybe there were other Jonkheers who did survive but we don’t have that data in our training set so we can collapse titles into more close title.

Title is indicative of Sex and Age.

First create a df with two columns - Title and New.Title Which is like a lookup table to map titles, for example Capt. Col. etc should be mapped to Mr.

Then for both dfs match on title and join the new column New.Title

Condense titles down to small subset left join with lookup table is a very general pattern for replacement in dplyr old value, new values to map

titles.lookup = data.frame( title = c("Mr.", "Capt.",
                                      "Col.", "Don.",
                                      "Dr.", "Jonkheer.",
                                      "Major.", "Rev.",
                                      "Sir.", "Mrs.",
                                      "Dona.", "Lady.",
                                      "Mme.", "Countess.",
                                      "Miss.","Mlle.", "Ms.",
                                      "Master."),
                            new.title=c(rep("Mr.",9),
                                        rep("Mrs.",5),
                                        rep("Miss.",3),
                                        "Master."),
                            stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

#View(titles.lookup)

# Replace Titles using lookup table join lookup df for matching titles with train df

train = train %>%
  left_join(titles.lookup, by = "title")

table(train$new.title)
## 
## Master.   Miss.     Mr.    Mrs. 
##      40     185     538     128
# Let's replace Title with New.Title and remove New.Title

train = train %>%
  mutate(title = new.title) %>%
  select(-new.title)

table(train$title)
## 
## Master.   Miss.     Mr.    Mrs. 
##      40     185     538     128
# Specific cases is overfit - avoid avoid avoid overfitting focus on generalization

# Alternatively you could do the above in one dplyr pipeline

train = train %>%
  left_join(titles.lookup, by = "title") %>%
  mutate(title=new.title) %>%
  select(-new.title)


table(train$title)
## 
## Master.   Miss.     Mr.    Mrs. 
##      40     185     538     128

5.4.1 Interpretation

There is lot of Age missing so we impute Age based on title and age average or median as replacement value or avg in some cases and median in some cases

let’s see the age statistics wrt Pclass and Title the older you are the wealthier you are stats and NAs for the group

age.stats = train %>%
  group_by(title,pclass) %>%
  summarize(age.min = min(age, na.rm = T),
            age.max = max(age, na.rm = T),
            age.mean = mean(age, na.rm = T),
            age.median = median(age, na.rm = T),
            age.na.count = sum(is.na(age)),
            age.var = var(age, na.rm = T),
            age.sd = sd(age, na.rm = T),
            age.IQR = IQR(age, na.rm = T)) %>%
  arrange(title,pclass)

#View(age.stats)

table(train$pclass)
## 
##   1   2   3 
## 216 184 491

Rule: When mean and median are close, it is better to use mean because it a good summary statistic

Miss is an overloaded title, it covers both unmarried adult women as well as female children. So Miss is problamatic for Title as proxy for Age. So for all titles except Miss we use mean age as proxy.

Rule Imputation Steps Create Tracking feature/ indicator variable- Y for NA else N lookup table

train$age.missing = ifelse(is.na(train$age), "Y","N")

table(train$age.missing)
## 
##   N   Y 
## 714 177
#View(train)

For matching Pclass and Title we want to replace NA age with mean / median Age So we create a new df with Pclass, Title, mean Age, median Age then join original df with this df on Pclass and Title then replace Age in original with either mean Age or median Age and remove the mean Age and median Age

age.lookup = age.stats %>%
  select(pclass,title,age.mean,age.median)

#View(age.lookup)


train = train %>%
  left_join(age.lookup, by=c("pclass","title")) %>%
  mutate(age = ifelse(age.missing == "Y",
                      ifelse(title == "Miss.", age.median, age.mean),
                      age) ) %>%
  select(-age.median, -age.mean)

#View(train)

We engineered feature title as it was proxy for gender and age

We imputed the below features

zero fares - median fares based on Pclass missing age - mean(except Miss)/median(Miss) age based on title and Pclass

Steps for imputing or replacing features

Create Tracking feature as indicator for replacing values - it helps to reverse engineer to original value if we need to later

Create a lookup table for new features using join - so we need to add the matching columns to the lookup table - left join original df with new - mutate to do the actual replacement - remove the lookup variables from original df

Here we’ll go ahead and create a whole lot of new features

look at impute Age distribution all up 5 % to 100% step by 5 percent 20 buckets

quantile(train$age, probs = c(0.25,0.5,0.75))

5.6.1 New feature family size

Let’s create a new feature family_size

A passenger who has parch or sbsp value non-zero implies is traveling with family sbsp is for spouse and parch is for parch If passenger is traveling with spouse, sbsp is 1 and if they have children the parch will have number of children traveling with them. If pasenger is child parch is either 0 or 1 or 2, if passenger is adult then parch is number of children

If passenger is traveling with sibling, sbsp is number of siblings and parch is number of parents 0 or 1 or 2

So family size siblings/spouse plus parch plus the individual passenger count

Tickets were bought for group not individual tickets for each seat as in modern day based on individuals with same ticket. Fare can be calculated for each individual based on title and age

# group by tickets and engineer below 13 features 

ticket.lookup = train %>%
  group_by(ticket) %>%
  summarize(group.count = n(),
            avg.fare = max(fare)/n(),
            female.count = sum(sex == "female"),
            male.count = sum(sex == "male"),
            child.count = sum(age < 18),
            elderly.count = sum(age > 54.0),
            female.ratio = sum(sex == "female")/n(),
            male.ratio = sum(sex == "male")/n(),
            child.ratio = sum(age < 18)/n(),
            elderly.ratio = sum(age > 54.0)/n(),
            female.child.ratio = ( sum(age <18) +
                                     sum(sex == "female" & age >= 18))/n(),
            min.age = min(age),
            max.age = max(age))
